equation_narrative.headline: Model misreads buried hydrophobic context, predicting alanine over serine at position 57
equation_narrative.story: Position 57 in ubiquitin sits in a complex structural environment with 5 spatial contacts and 2 co-evolving positions. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation dominated by hydrophobic signals from nearby leucine and valine residues, causing the logit lens to project toward hydrophobic amino acids (L peaks at 30% at L21, A rises steadily). The representation character shifts dramatically at L23-25 as prediction channels activate. In the decision phase (L24-33), alanine-specific features surge while serine briefly peaks at 35% at L26 before losing ground. The model commits to alanine with 63% confidence, underweighting the polar character needed at this position.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather structural and evolutionary context through attention heads that read local sequence and spatial neighbors. The model processes 5 structural contacts and 2 co-evolving positions, with attention heads at L8-9 showing strong local reading patterns (F9:5728 with 49.5 proj, F9:1281 with 45.4 proj). The representation character is initially hydrophobic-leaning: the logit lens projects toward leucine (peaks at 30% L21) and alanine (rises from 6% at L8 to 17% at L23), reflecting the buried hydrophobic environment being encoded. By L18, abstract structural features emerge (F18:9851 with 26.2 proj, F18:4071 with 23.0 proj) that encode the position's context. The representation remains ambiguous through L23, consistent with small hydrophobic or polar residues, before prediction channels activate.
perception_phase.context_character: The biochemical context assembled by L23 is predominantly hydrophobic with local sequence neighbors including leucine (L56) and threonine (L55), suggesting a partially buried environment. The representation is consistent with small, flexible residues that could fit in a constrained structural pocket.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 5 residues within 8Å, read through attention heads at L8-12
Co-evolutionary signal: 2 coupled positions detected, indicating functional constraints
L9 attention features: F9:5728 (49.5 proj) and F9:1281 (45.4 proj) encode local hydrophobic context
L18 structural features: F18:9851 (26.2 proj) and F18:4071 (23.0 proj) capture abstract position properties

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L24-25 when alanine-specific prediction channels activate and serine briefly surges to 30% at L25. Serine peaks at 35% at L26 but then loses ground as alanine-supporting MLP neurons dominate L29-32. Key alanine writers include N30:3818 (0.72 proj), N31:3170 (1.53 proj), and N32:2817 (0.84 proj). By L33, attention heads deliver the final push: L31 head 5 writes 2.58 toward serine, but L30 head 12 writes 2.44 toward alanine, and the model commits to alanine at 63%.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from encoding context to predicting specific amino acids. Serine leads at 20% at L23, then alanine takes over at 21% at L24. AA-specific prediction features first appear at L24 (F24:10131 with 16.9 proj, F24:217 with 16.5 proj), marking the transition from perception to decision.

candidates.narrative: Alanine emerges as the winner through sustained MLP support in L29-32. N30:3818 contributes 0.72 proj, N31:3170 delivers a massive 1.53 proj (also supporting S, R, H), and N32:2817 adds 0.84 proj. The final surge comes at L31-33: attention head L31:5 writes 2.58 (though this also supports serine), and L30:12 writes 2.44 specifically for alanine. Alanine rises from 19% at L29 to 63% at L33, winning decisively.
key_evidence: N31:3170 (1.53 proj) — massive multi-polar support including alanine
L30 head 12 (2.44 proj) — local writer favoring alanine
L31 head 5 (2.58 proj) — local writer with mixed support

candidates.narrative: Serine is the correct answer but loses to alanine. It leads early (23% at L0, 20% at L23) and surges at L25-26, peaking at 35% at L26 with strong MLP support from N25:3933 (0.61 proj) and N25:4444 (0.48 proj). However, serine loses ground in L27-29 as alanine-supporting neurons dominate. Despite late support from L31 head 5 (2.58 proj), serine finishes at 20%, unable to overcome the hydrophobic bias encoded in earlier layers.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L0-L23, peaks L26, fades L27-29
key_evidence: N25:3933 (0.61 proj) — serine-specific writer at decision onset
L31 head 5 (2.58 proj) — late attempt to recover serine

candidates.narrative: Leucine dominates the logit lens in the perception phase, reflecting the hydrophobic character of the representation as the model reads nearby leucine residues in the structural context. It peaks at 30% at L21, leading from L13-L20. This is NOT a prediction — it indicates the representation is strongly hydrophobic-leaning as the model encodes the buried environment. Leucine fades rapidly after L23 as prediction channels activate, finishing at negligible probability.
key_evidence: Logit lens peaks at 30% L21 — representation is maximally hydrophobic
Reflects structural contacts with hydrophobic residues
Disappears after L23 when prediction channels activate

candidates.narrative: Glycine maintains steady low-level support (2-6%) throughout processing, consistent with its role as a flexible, small residue that could fit in constrained environments. It peaks at 10% at L32, suggesting late-stage consideration of conformational flexibility. However, it never gains strong MLP or attention support and finishes at 6%.
key_evidence: Consistent low-level presence reflects flexibility consideration
Late peak at L32 (10%) suggests final flexibility check

candidates.narrative: Glutamine shows transient support in mid-layers, peaking at 13% at L28 before fading. This reflects brief consideration of polar side-chain functionality, but glutamine-erasing neurons dominate (N28:4773 with -0.74 proj against serine also erases Q). It finishes at 2%, unable to compete with the hydrophobic bias.
key_evidence: N28:4773 (-0.74 proj) — strong eraser affecting both Q and polar candidates

turning_points.description: The representation becomes maximally hydrophobic as the model integrates structural contacts. Leucine rises from 14% at L13 to 30% at L21, dominating the logit lens. This reflects the model encoding the buried, hydrophobic environment around position 57. MLP layers L14-L19 show net negative projection toward serine (total -3.03 at L19), actively suppressing polar character. This hydrophobic bias, appropriate for encoding context but problematic for prediction, persists into the decision phase.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. At L23, serine leads at 20% with the representation still ambiguous. At L24, alanine takes over at 21% as AA-specific features activate (F24:10131, F24:217). Serine surges at L25-26, peaking at 35% with strong MLP support (N25:3933 0.61 proj, N25:4444 0.48 proj), but this is the high-water mark. The model is choosing between small polar (S) and small hydrophobic (A) residues, with the decision still fluid.

Alanine decisively wins through coordinated MLP and attention support. L29 MLP erases serine (total -3.36 MLP delta), dropping it from 16% to final 20%. L30-L32 MLPs strongly support alanine: N30:3818 (0.72), N31:3170 (1.53), N32:2817 (0.84). Final attention heads at L30-31 deliver the decisive push: L30 head 12 writes 2.44 for alanine, L31 head 5 writes 2.58 (mixed support). Alanine surges from 19% to 63%, while serine stabilizes at 20%.

deep_dives.label: Structural reading L8-12
deep_dives.caption: These layers read structural contacts and local sequence. L8 head 6 writes 2.25 without clear source (diffuse structural reading). L12 head 2 erases -2.31, suggesting conflict between local and structural signals. This is where the hydrophobic bias originates.

deep_dives.label: Context encoding L9-L18
deep_dives.caption: L9 features (F9:5728 49.5 proj, F9:1281 45.4 proj) encode local hydrophobic context. L18 features (F18:9851 26.2 proj, F18:4071 23.0 proj) capture abstract structural properties. These shape the hydrophobic-leaning representation that biases the final decision.

deep_dives.label: Prediction channels L24
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the perception-to-decision transition. F24:10131 (16.9 proj) and F24:217 (16.5 proj) are the first AA-specific prediction features, activating as the model shifts from encoding context to predicting specific amino acids.

deep_dives.label: Serine surge L25-L26
deep_dives.caption: Serine's strongest moment. L25 MLP delivers +3.22 total (N25:3933 0.61 proj, N25:4444 0.48 proj), pushing serine to 30%. L26 sees the peak at 35%, but net MLP is -3.20 as erasers begin to dominate. This is where the model seriously considers the correct answer before rejecting it.

deep_dives.label: Alanine MLP support L29-L32
deep_dives.caption: The decisive MLP layers. L29 erases serine (-3.36 MLP delta). L30-L32 strongly support alanine: N30:3818 (0.72), N31:3170 (1.53), N32:2817 (0.84). These neurons cast the votes that determine the final prediction.

deep_dives.label: Final attention L30-L32
deep_dives.caption: The last information flow. L30 head 12 writes 2.44 for alanine (local reading). L31 head 5 writes 2.58 (mixed support for S/A). L32 head 12 erases -1.58 from serine. These heads deliver the final evidence that locks in the alanine prediction.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model assembles a representation dominated by hydrophobic structural contacts, causing the logit lens to project toward leucine and alanine through L23. When prediction channels activate at L24-26, serine briefly surges to 35% as the model considers polar functionality, but the hydrophobic bias encoded in earlier layers proves decisive. MLP neurons at L29-L32 strongly support alanine (N31:3170 contributes 1.53 proj), and final attention heads at L30-31 deliver the winning votes. The model predicts alanine at 63%, misreading the position's need for polar character and underweighting the serine signal that peaked at L26.
